# VEASNA Offline/LAN-First Rule

## Core Context
- Treat VEASNA as an offline/local-network-first application.
- Assume backend, frontend, and PostgreSQL run on one host laptop.
- Assume client devices connect from the same private subnet.
- Prefer host IP access patterns over localhost-only assumptions.

## Implementation Priorities
- Keep core workflows functional without internet.
- Prefer simple, reliable local deployment over cloud-dependent architecture.
- Preserve data integrity and attribution for future sync to central DB.

## Networking and Environment
- Prefer host binding where relevant (`0.0.0.0`).
- Keep CORS/API config compatible with LAN IP origins.
- Avoid introducing hard dependencies on external services for core features.

## Authentication Guidance
- Keep lightweight username/password auth unless user asks otherwise.
- Do not introduce complex role systems unless explicitly requested.
- Preserve user attribution fields (e.g., updater identity and timestamps).

## Change Management
- When changes affect setup, update README documentation.
- If a proposal conflicts with offline/LAN goals, present an offline-safe alternative.

## Engineering Quality Expectations
- Prefer simple, readable, and maintainable code over clever complexity.
- Keep implementations modular: extract shared components/utilities for repeated patterns.
- Minimize scope of each change; avoid unrelated edits in the same task.
- Maintain backward compatibility for APIs, data shape, and clinic workflows unless explicitly requested.
- Validate changes with lint/tests when available, and resolve newly introduced issues.
- Handle errors explicitly and preserve actionable logging/messages.
- Remove obvious duplication/dead code and keep naming consistent.
- Document setup or behavior changes in relevant README files.
